This long diseourse which Simo holds with Sosia is well conceived by the poet, as it serves to explain -the fable, and give us such an insight into the plot, as is necessary to make us under- stand it. The whole too is so contrived, that we find ourselves in- sensibly prepossessed in favour of the chief persons of the play, and cannot avoid interesting ourselves in their fortune, which is one of the grand secrets in this way of writing. -—-2.
